1. What is Node.js?

Node.js is a runtime environment that allows you to run JavaScript outside the browser.
Instead of being limited to web pages, you can build servers, tools, and
backend applications using JavaScript.

2. Installing Node.js (OS-neutral)
Go to the official website: https://nodejs.org
Download the LTS (Long Term Support) version
Run the installer and follow the setup steps
Ensure the option to add Node to your system PATH is enabled (usually default)

node -v

npm -v



4. Understanding the REPL

Before writing files, it's helpful to understand the REPL.
REPL stands for:
Read
Eval
Print
Loop

It’s an interactive environment where you can type JavaScript and see results instantly.

Start it by typing:
node

> 2 + 3
5
> console.log("Hello")
Hello
.exit


Running Your Script

In the terminal, navigate to the file location and run:
node app.js

Output:
Hello, Node.js!
This shows how Node executes JavaScript outside the browser.


Creating a Simple Hello World Server

Now let’s create a basic server using Node’s built-in module:

const http = require('http');
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.end("Hello World from Node.js server!");
});
server.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Server running at http://localhost:3000");
});


node app.js
http://localhost:3000




